comments.body:
@ferrieux I am still unsure what logic needs to be added to the stack.  If the receiver stack received a valid packet, it will ACK it in due time.  If that packet contained an ACK-eliciting frame, the ACK will have a tight "deadline" when it must go out (if the packet contained no ACK-eliciting frames, the ACK may be delayed significantly). DATAGRAM is an ACK-eliciting frame. 

The sender will know which packets were lost with the same degree of reliability, regardless of whether the packets contained STREAM or DATAGRAM frames.  It can maintain L counter equally well when DATAGRAM is used.

What am I missing?

@ferrieux 
> In addition to the spin bit, there's also the IP.id in IPv4.

If IP.id often helpful for reordering fixup?  Linux sets IP.id=0, unless there are fragments.
